You’ll find this in various guises and various names across the Balkans and Eastern Europe, Greece and Turkey, all the way to Armenia and North Africa….. it’s the Borek Belt! 😂

It’s made with all sorts of filling options, but for me, I can’t go past lamb. The spices are intoxicating (cinnamon is the secret!), and I adore the pine nuts / currants combo.

For a veg option, use the filling from my Spana recipe - it’s so good!! - N x ❤️

PS To make the Melb Queen Victorian Markets Borek version, just shape into individual size logs instead of spiral, same bake time.👌🏻

Borek – with Spiced Lamb (Turkish version)

INGREDIENTS:
FILLING: 2 tbsp olive oil, 1 onion finely diced,  2 garlic cloves finely minced, 600g / 1.2 lb lamb mince (sub beef), 1 1/2 tsp ground cumin, 3/4 tsp EACH ground coriander, cinnamon, paprika,  1/2 tsp allspice (sub mixed spice), 1/2 tsp cayenne pepper, 1/2 tsp black pepper,  1 1/4 tsp cooking / kosher salt,  1/3 cup currants (or similar), 1/3 cup pine nuts toasted,  1 cup tomato passata (tomato puree in US), 1/4 cup water
YOGURT WASH FOR FILO (STOPS CRACKING) - mix: 1 egg, 2 tbsp plain yogurt, 30g / 2 tbsp unsalted butter melted
PASTRY: 12 sheets phyllo pastry, 25g / 1 1/2 tbsp unsalted butter melted and cooled,  White sesame seeds (optional)
LEMON YOGURT SAUCE - mix: 1 cup plain yogurt, 1/4 tsp garlic finely grated, 1 tbsp lemon juice, 1 tbsp extra virgin olive oil,  Pinch of salt

DIRECTIONS
1. Filling: Heat oil on high, cook onion & garlic 2 min, add lamb, cook until changes from pink to brown. Add all spices, cook 1 min. Add everything else, stir, simmer on low 5 min until liquid mostly evaporated, but still juicy. Fully cool.
2. Flick yogurt wash onto filo then lightly brush (don’t need to cover every inch). Repeat for 4 layers (don’t brush top layer). Roll with 1/3 of lamb. Repeat to make 3 rolls. Roll into spiral on paper (use yogurt wash to connect). Slide into butter greased 26cm / 10.5″ cast iron skillet (or freeform on tray). Brush with butter, sprinkle with sesame seeds. Bake 200°C / 390°F (180°C fan) 40 min until golden. Cut wedges like pie, serve with yogurt sauce!

If I can do it with my chubby little hands, it’ll be a breeze for you! As for what to make with it? Coming later today. IT’S EPIC!!!
.
UPDATE: to those raising concerns, putting it in the freezer is a humane way to dispatch a crab. It goes into a coma, no mental or physical activity, so feels nothing when you break it up. The other way is to spike it through central nerves. But you can miss. Freezer is easier. I did a lot of research on this topic.
.
Full directions step by step are on my website - https://www.recipetineats.com/how-to-clean-and-cut-a-whole-crab/
.

You'll love how the cake is lovely and moist (too often they are terribly dry!), and how it’s not too sweet so you can actually taste all the elements. Looks rich and decadent, but is actually not that rich at all – so you can eat plenty! 😋 - N x ❤️
.
PS I specifically use jarred cherries NOT fresh. They're softer so texturally they make more sense, plus the flavoured syrup from the jar is perfect to brush the cake layers. Just not the same using fresh cherries! 

Black Forest Cake
.
CHOC CAKE: 6 large eggs (room temp), 1 tsp vanilla, 1 1/4 cup caster/superfine sugar, 1/2 cup dutch processed cocoa powder (or regular), 2/3 cup plain/all-purpose flour, 150g/10.5 tbsp unsalted butter (melted cooled)
CHERRY SYRUP: 670g / 23.5 oz pitted morello cherries in syrup (sour cherries, jar or can) , drained & juice reserved, 1/3 cup kirsch or cherry liqueur (sub more cherry syrup), 1/2 cup caster /superfine sugar, 4 tsp cornflour/cornstarch
CREAM - whip: 4 cups/1 litre thickened/heavy cream, 2 tsp vanilla, 1/3 cup soft icing sugar / powdered sugar.
DECORATING: 100g / 3.5 oz dark/bittersweet chocolate to make curls, 12 maraschino or fresh cherries
.
1. Sift flour & cocoa, set aside. Beat eggs 30 sec speed 6. Add sugar over 45 sec with beat on, then add vanilla. Beat 7 min on speed 8, tripled volume pale white. Fold in flour/cocoa, then fold in butter. Bake 25 min 180°C / 350°F (160°C fan) in 3 x 20cm (8”) cake pans (greased & lined). Cool 10 min then cool on racks.
2. Mix ¼ cup cherry juice with cornflour. Dissolve sugar in another 1/3 cup cherry juice in saucepan over med heat. Add cornflour slurry, simmer 1 min until thin syrup. Add to cherries, cool.
3. Brush 3 tbsp syrup on cake, spread with 1 cup cream, top with half cherries. Top with cake, then repeat syrup > cream > cherries. Top with cake, brush with ¼ cup syrup, cover cake with cream. Pipe cream swirls around edge, top with cherries. Pile choc curls in centre. Leave 4 hrs in fridge to overnight before serving! Keeps 3 - 4 days.
.

I promise I take constructive criticism well. 😇 - N x ❤️
.
Turkish Pide (Flat bread / Turkish Pizza)
.
DOUGH (MAKES 2): 1 tsp rapid rise / instant yeast (sub active dry yeast), 1/2 tsp white sugar, 2 tbsp + 2/3 cups very warm water, 2 cups bread flour (sub all purpose/plain), 3/4 tsp salt, 1 1/2 tsp olive oil
ASSEMBLING: 150g / 5oz Turkish kasar cheese or mozzarella, 1/2 tsp semolina (optional)
SPINACH TOPPING: 2 tsp olive oil, 1/2 onion finely diced, 280g/10oz baby spinach, 1/2 tsp EACH cumin, pepper, 1/4 tsp salt
TURKISH SAUSAGE TOPPING (SUJUK): 125g / 4oz Turkish Sujuk sausage (sub chorizo)
LAMB TOPPING: 1 tbsp olive oil, 1/2 onion finely diced, 1 garlic clove finely minced, 250g / 8oz lamb mince (or beef), 1 tsp tomato paste, 1 tsp Baharat spice mix, 1/2 tsp cumin, 1/8 tsp each salt & pepper, 1/2 red capsicum / bell pepper & 1/2 tomato finely chopped, 1 tsp lemon juice
SPRINKLING FINISHES – CHOOSE: 4 tbsp Turkish Tulum cheese or feta (crumbled), dried oregano, Sesame seeds toasted, Sumac, Coriander/cilantro leaves, Extra virgin olive oil
.
1. DOUGH: Mix yeast w/2 tbsp water + sugar, stand 10 min until foamy. Mix with flour, salt and olive oil, knead 8 min until smooth (stand mixer 3 min speed 6). Rise 1.5 hrs until doubled in size. Punch down, halve, shape into balls, rise on floured tray covered with damp tea towel.
2. ASSEMBLE: Roll out into 40 x 20cm / 16 x 8” oval shape, sprinkle tray with semolina. Place dough on, sprinkle with cheese & topping of choice, leaving 2 cm/ 0.8” border. Brush end with water, pinch to seal, then fold sides in. Bake 15 min at 240°C/465°F (220°C fan). (EGG OPTION – crack on top when 5 min bake time left). Sprinkle with Finishes of choice (any combo works!), cut into slices & serve! 
3. SPINACH: Heat oil medium high, cook onion, wilt spinach, stir in seasonings.
4. SAUSAGE: Blitz to turn into mince, then crumble across pide surface.
5. LAMB: Heat oil medium high, cook onion and garlic, cook lamb, add everything else and cook until all liquid evaporates (3 – 5 min).
.

That moment when he blows out the candles…😂😂😂
.
HAPPY BIRTHDAY DOZER!!! - N x ❤️
.
DOZER’S 9TH BIRTHDAY CAKE!! 🎉🎂
.
Whipped potato might sound like a weird frosting, but it looks and behaves like buttercream frosting and DOGS don’t care!!! 
.
DOG Friendly BIRTHDAY CAKE:
2 eggs, 1/2 cup (120g) peanut butter (spread or pure), 1/4 cup oil (canola, veg)
2/3 cup milk (or water), 1/3 cup honey or maple syrup (or apple sauce or skip it), 2 1/2 cups shredded carrot (2 large), 2 cups (300g) whole wheat / wholemeal or white flour (plain/all purpose), 2.5 tsp baking soda
DOG FRIENDLY FLUFFY FROSTING (WHIPPED POTATO YOGURT): 1 kg / 2 lb potatoes , peeled, cut into chunks, 1 cup yogurt (plain unsweetened) or water, blue gel colouring (I used Sky Blue by Wilton) or food colouring
DRIP FROSTING: 1/2 cup cornflour/cornstarch, 1/4 cup plain yogurt, 1 – 2 tbsp milk (as needed)
.
1. Whisk eggs, peanut butter, oil, milk and honey. Stir in carrot, then flour and baking soda until JUST incorporated.
2. Divide between 2 x 15cm/6” pans that are 7.5cm/3” deep (grease and line). Bake 180C/350F (160C fan) for 30 min or until skewer comes out clean. Cool on rack, trim top to make it flat, then cut each cake in half.
3. Cook potato until VERY soft (boil, steam, microwave). Whip with yogurt plus extra water to achieve soft, spreadable consistency.
4. Spread ~2/3 cup frosting between each layer. Then colour the remaining frosting with your desired colour (I did 2 x toothpick dips into gel/ smear on surface of mash). Frost cake.
5. Mix Drip Frosting ingredients, do a test consistency – should drip slowly down vertical side. Spread frosting on top of cake first, then use teaspoon to make drips. Decorate with silver balls etc as desired then refrigerate immediately to set Drip Frosting. Store in fridge until ready to serve!!
.

Bake with me! Hear the story of ANZAC Day - and take a moment to remember those who fought and lost their lives for us.
.
Lest We Forget. - Nagi & Dozer 🌹
.
Anzac Biscuits
.
1 cup (150g) plain flour
1 cup (100g) rolled oats
1 cup (80g) desiccated coconut
3/4 cup (165g) white sugar , preferably caster / superfine
150g / 5oz unsalted butter
4 tbsp golden syrup (sub 1 tbsp light molasses OR treacle plus 3 tbsp honey)
1 tsp baking soda (bicarbonate soda)
.
DIRECTIONS
1. Mix flour, oats, coconut and sugar.
2. Melt butter with golden syrup over medium heat. Once it starts bubbling, add the baking soda. Stir to dissolve - it will foam!
3. Pour into flour mixture, mix until combined.
4. Scoop up 1 tbsp of mixture, roll into ball then flatten into a thinnish patty (they don’t spread much). For standard size you buy in packets at the supermarket, use 2 tsp of mixture.
5. Place on paper lined trays 2.5cm/1” apart. Bake 15 min at 180C/350F (160C fan) for crisp ANZAC biscuits or until deep golden, or 12 minutes or until golden for chewy centres.
6. Cool 5 min on tray then transfer to cooling racks. They will be soft when warm but will crisp up when cooled. Crispy ones stay crispy for a week in an airtight container, after that they soften but still super tasty. Also can crisp up in oven – 5 min at same temp!
.
For more detailed directions, including step & ingredient photos and a full video recipe tutorial, please see the recipe on my website - search “Anzac biscuits” on www.recipetineats.com (link in bio)
.

Bringing some French sophistication to your weekend in the form of Crème Brûlée! So very tres chic, so very easy, this is quite possibly the king of all custards. Ultra smooth, velvety and rich yet somehow also delicate at the same time, this is a fab elegant dessert for dinner parties because it’s make ahead. So you can totally nail the poised-dinner-host thing. If you’re into that sort of thing. Me - I try. But as you’ve seen over the years on IG stories, I start off the cook looking poised and end up a sweaty frightful mess. 😂 - N x ❤️
.
Crème Brûlée
.
2 cups pure cream (Aus) / heavy cream (US)
1 vanilla pod OR 1 tsp vanilla bean paste
5 egg yolks 
1/4 cup caster sugar (superfine sugar)
TOFFEE TOPPING: 2 tsp caster sugar (superfine sugar)
.
1. Scrape vanilla bean seeds out of vanilla pod. Put the seeds, used pod and cream in a saucepan, simmer on low heat 10 min. Remove from stove, stand 1 hour uncovered. Remove bean and scoop off any skin formed on surface. 
2. Whisk yolks and sugar in a bowl until just combined. Stir in cream – don’t overstir, we don’t have bubbles in our custard.
3. Divide between 4 x 150ml / 2/3 cup ramekins. Place in baking pan, fill with boiling water up to halfway. Bake 35 minutes at 130°C/265°F (120°C fan) – should be set (ie not water) but still jiggles when you gently shake it. 
4. Cool then refrigerate 6 hrs (up to 3 days). Sprinkle with sugar, blast with blow torch to melt and caramelise. Serve immediately. OR put under super hot broiler/grill 1 min, the fridge 20 min – 1 hr, then serve.

.

I’m going to call it - this is the most delicious Cauliflower recipe I know. Big, BIG call - but I’m standing by it!!
.
This is a pretty common side you’ll find at high end steakhouses or a particularly lavish Sunday roast. It’s unapologetically indulgent, intended to replicate the luxury you’d expect from such establishments! So while it’s not the same, you can cut calories by switching the cream for milk, and reducing some of the cheese (I can’t believe I just wrote that🙀) 
.
Be on theme - try it alongside steak or any seared protein, or roast chicken, beef, pork or lamb. Devour and be prepared to swoon…. - N x ❤️
.
Cauliflower Cheese (Bake/Gratin)
.
ROASTED CAULIFLOWER (SO much tastier than boiling!):
1kg / 2 lb cauliflower florets (1.25 / 2.5lb whole 1 very large head, 1 1/2 medium or 2 small)
2 tbsp extra virgin olive oil
1/2 tsp sea salt
1/8 tsp pepper
CHEESE SAUCE (MORNAY SAUCE):
60g / 4 tbsp unsalted butter
30g / 3½ tbsp flour , plain / all-purpose
1 cup milk (full fat best) + 1 cup cream (or more milk), heated until hot but not boiling
1/2 tsp cooking salt (kosher salt)
1/4 tsp nutmeg powder (freshly grated is best)
100g / 1 cup Red Leicester cheese (or cheddar, or other melting cheese), grated
50g / ½ cup gruyère cheese , grated (or other melting cheese of choice)
TOPPING: 1/2 cup (50g) EACH Red Leicester cheese and Gruyere
.
1. Toss cauliflower in salt, pepper and oil. Bake 220C/430F (200C fan) for 20 min, no turning. Should be slightly undercooked still, with a bit of colour. 
2. Meanwhile, melt butter in small pot or large saucepan over medium heat. Add flour, stir 3 min. Pour in half milk while stirring, then once it’s mostly lump free, stir in remaining milk. Use whisk if needed to remove lumps. Cook 1 min – should be thick enough to coat wooden spoon (see vid). Turn off stove (but keep pot on stove), stir in cheese, salt and nutmeg. Should be thick but pourable.
3. Add cauliflower, stir to coat. Transfer mixture to a 2L / 2qt baking dish (30 x 20 x 5cm / 12 x 8 x 2"). Top with cheese, bake 180C/350F 30 min until bubbly and golden (all oven types). Sprinkle with parsley, serve!

.

Weekend cooking project!! Well, one of them 😊 I have another one for you tomorrow!
.
Introducing the little sister of the famous Beef Pho - Chicken Pho! Equally delicious, but sooo much easier to make. 👌🏻 - N x ❤️
.
Chicken Pho (4 big servings, 6 light servings)
.
CHARRED AROMATICS: 1 tbsp oil, 2 onions halved (skin on), 5cm/ 2" piece of ginger , sliced 0.75cm / 1/3" thick (unpeeled)
PHO SOUP BROTH:
2 litres / 2 quarts water
1.5 kg / 3 lb chicken thighs, bone in skin on  OR whole chicken
1 small bunch coriander/cilantro, 5 star anise pods, 1 cinnamon stick, 4 cloves, 2 tsp EACH fennel & coriander seeds, 8 tsp fish sauce, 6 tsp white sugar, 1/2 tsp salt
BOWLS: 
360g / 13 oz dried rice noodles, thin flat (or 600g fresh)
2 green onions stems , finely sliced
TOPPINGS - HELP YOURSELF: 3 cups bean sprouts, 1 small bunch EACH Thai Basil, min, coriander/cilantro*, 2 limes, Hoisin sauce, Sriracha, Red chillies finely sliced (optional)
.
1. Heat oil in 6 litre/6 quart+ pot over high heat. Place onion & ginger cut face down, leave 2 min until black, turn leave 2 min.
2. Add all Broth ingredients EXCEPT salt. Bring to simmer, then put lid on leaving it open a crack, adjust heat so it’s simmering gently. Scoop off foam once or twice, simmer 1.5 hrs.
3. Remove chicken (shred meat), then strain into new pot. Should be 1.5 litres/1.5 quarts – measure, simmer to reduce or add water to top up. 
4. Add 1/2 tsp salt into broth – taste. Should be slightly salty (dilutes when served over noodles etc). Keep it piping hot while you prepare Toppings.
5. Prepare noodles per packet, drain very well, immediately put in bowls. Top with some chicken, ladle over broth, sprinkle with green onions. Serve like that, let people put everything else on themselves!

.

🥦🥦🥦This is how you turn a head of broccoli into the most amazing soup. It’s creamy and CHEESY. You know it’s a winner! - N x❤️

PS Bread for dunking is not optional. Preferably garlic bread. Or, even better - cheesy bread. 😳

Thick & Creamy Broccoli Cheese Soup
.
INGREDIENTS
1 tbsp butter
2 garlic cloves, minced 
1 onion, diced (brown, white yellow)
4 cups chicken or vegetable broth / stock, low sodium
1½ cups water
1.4lb/700g broccoli, cut into florets + cut thick skin off stem and dice
2 potatoes, peeled and diced into ⅔"/1.5cm cubes
2 cups cheddar or tasty cheese, shredded
3/4 cup cream OR milk
Salt and pepper
Garnishes: More cheese, cream, chives or parsley
.
DIRECTIONS
1. Melt butter in large pot over medium high. Cook garlic and onion 3 min.
2. Add broth, water, broccoli, potato. Bring to boil, then adjust heat so it’s simmering, 
Cover, simmer 20 minutes until broccoli is very soft,
3. Blitz with stick blender (or cool slightly then use blender). 
4. Stir in cream, then stir in cheese a handful at a time. Adjust salt and pepper to 
taste.
5. Ladle into bowls. Drizzle with cream and top with extra grated cheese, if desired.

My favourite all-rounder rub for pork chops. BONUS: Throw in a knob of butter at the end and you have an instant flavoured sauce! - N x ❤️

Just a great Pork Rub

Pork Rub mix:
1 tbsp smoked paprika
2 1/4 tsp cooking/kosher salt (or 1 3/4 tsp table salt)
3/4 tsp black pepper
1 1/2 tsp garlic powder
1 1/2 tsp onion powder
1 tsp dried oregano
3/4 tsp mustard powder
1/2 tsp cumin powder
1/2 tsp sage powder
Pork:
Pork chops of choice
1 1/2 tbsp olive oil per batch of pork chops cooked
1 tbsp / 15 g butter per pork chop (for flavoured butter sauce)

1. Pat pork dry then sprinkle and rub with seasoning. Shake off excess.
2. Heat oil in heavy based skillet over medium high heat. 
3. THICK chops 2 cm / 0.8″+ - Sear edges first using tongs (rotate ~ 3 min) then sear each side 2 min until golden. Leave in skillet and transfer to oven 180°C/350°F for 3 min or until internal temp is 65°C/149°F. Rest on rack 3 min. Meanwhile, melt butter in skillet, scrape base to dissolve golden bits into sauce. Serve with chops!
3. THIN chops up to 1.75cm / 0.7” – Cook 3 min each side or until internal temp is 65°C/149°F. Rest 3 min, meanwhile, melt butter in skillet. Serve with chops!

#recipetineats #porkchops

node.text:
Old school Aussie Chinese takeout favourite - MONGOLIAN LAMB!!

The sauce for this one was irritatingly hard to get right. But we got there! Plus, you’ll love the little trick to tenderise economical lamb cuts so it’s SUPER tender, just like you get at Chinese restaurants. 

Hope you love this as much as I do! - N x ❤️

Mongolian Lamb
.
LAMB AND MARINADE:
350g / 12 oz lamb meat*, thinly sliced 2 - 3 mm / 1/10", 1/2 tsp baking soda (bicarb soda), 1 tsp cornflour / cornstarch, 1 tbsp light soy sauce (or all purpose), 1 tbsp Chinese cooking wine
SAUCE - Mix: 1 1/2 tsp Sambal Oelak or other chilli paste (or omit for no spice), 2 tbsp Chinese cooking wine^, 3 tbsp hoisin sauce, 1/4 tsp five spice powder, 2 tsp dark soy sauce, 1 tsp light soy sauce (or all purpose), 3/4 cup water, 2 tsp cornflour / cornstarch, 1 tsp sesame oil (toasted)
STIR FRY: 2 tbsp veg or canola oil, 1 large onion (2.5cm / 1" squares), 2 cloves garlic finely chopped, 4 green onions (5cm/2" lengths)
.
1. Mix Lamb and Marinade well. Marinate Tender Cuts for 2 hrs, and Economical Cuts for 24 hrs (see List below)
2. Heat oil in large skillet over high heat. Cook onion 1 min, then add garlic, cook 15 sec. Add lamb, cook for 2 min until mostly browned (some pink ok, you want some golden bits too), add green onion cook 30 sec. 
3. Add sauce, stir, cook 1 1/2 min to 2 min until it thickens into a glossy sauce (it’s quick). Serve with rice!
.
* Tender Cuts - backstrap / fillet / loin, mid loin chops, chump chop and lamb rump (roast or steak)
Economical Cuts - lamb shoulder, leg (steak or roast), forequarter chops and neck (bit fatty but really great lamb flavour)
Beef – excellent too! See recipe on website for list of suitable cuts.

#recipetineats #chinesetakeout #mongolianlamb

node.text:
The BEST cauliflower dish ever. Full stop, end of discussion, no arguments! 

If you haven’t tried it, you’re missing out. DO IT! (And, cauliflowers are super cheap right now!) - N x ❤️

Cauliflower Cheese (Bake/Gratin)
.
ROASTED CAULIFLOWER:
1kg / 2 lb cauliflower florets (1.25 / 2.5lb whole 1 very large head, 1 1/2 medium or 2 small) 2 tbsp extra virgin olive oil 1/2 tsp sea salt 1/8 tsp pepper
CHEESE SAUCE (MORNAY SAUCE):
60g / 4 tbsp unsalted butter
30g / 3½ tbsp flour , plain / all-purpose
1 cup milk (full fat best) + 1 cup cream (or more milk), heated until hot but not boiling
1/2 tsp cooking salt (kosher salt) 1/4 tsp nutmeg powder (freshly grated is best)
100g / 1 cup Red Leicester cheese (or cheddar, or other melting cheese), grated
50g / ½ cup gruyère cheese , grated (or other melting cheese of choice)
TOPPING: 1/2 cup (50g) EACH Red Leicester cheese and Gruyere
.
1. Toss cauliflower in salt, pepper and oil. Bake 220C/430F (200C fan) for 20 min, no turning. 
Should be slightly undercooked still, with a bit of colour. 
2. Meanwhile, melt butter in small pot or large saucepan over medium heat. Add flour, stir 3 min. Pour in half milk while stirring, then once it’s mostly lump free, stir in remaining milk. Use whisk if needed to remove lumps. Cook 1 min – should be thick enough to coat wooden spoon (see vid). Turn off stove (but keep pot on stove), stir in cheese, salt and nutmeg. Should be thick 
but pourable.
3. Add cauliflower, stir to coat. Transfer mixture to a 2L / 2qt baking dish (30 x 20 x 5cm / 12 x 8 x 2"). Top with cheese, bake 180C/350F 30 min until bubbly and golden (all oven types). Sprinkle with parsley, serve!

This one’s for everyone whose missing eating out at posh restaurants! The white wine sauce is totally fine dining worthy - but is actually super simple to make. The trick is stirring in cubes of cold butter at the end. It thickens the sauce and makes it all shiny and glossy, and gives it a lovely luxurious mouthfeel. (Technique called “monter au beurre” in French - if you wanna geek out!😂)

Use this for literally any fish than can be pan fried! - N x ❤️

White Wine Sauce for Fish

FISH:
4 x 150g / 5oz white fish fillets , skinless, boneless (I used snapper, any white fish fillets or salmon fine)
1/2 tsp salt, 1/4 tsp pepper, 2 tbsp extra virgin olive oil
WHITE WINE SAUCE:
1 eschalot , small, finely chopped (~1 1/2 tbsp)
1 1/4 cups white wine , dry, not sweet or too woody (chardonnay is especially good, non alcoholic - sub low sodium chicken stock)
1 tsp lemon juice (sub white wine vinegar), 1 tsp white wine vinegar (sub more lemon)
1/8 tsp salt, 1 pinch pepper, 1 pinch white sugar, 1 cup thickened/heavy cream
30g / 2 tbsp unsalted butter, cold, cut into 1cm / 1/3″ cubes
2 tsp finely chopped parsley (or chives), optional garnish

1. Sprinkle fish with salt and pepper. Heat oil over medium high in non stick pan. Cook fish in two batches, 2 min each side until golden (for 1.75cm / 2/3" thick fillets) or until the internal temperature is 55°C/131°F. Put on rack on tray, keep warm in 50°C/120°F oven.
2. Discard any excess oil in pan but don’t wipe clean. Add eschalot, wine, lemon, vinegar, salt, pepper, sugar, bring to simmer, reduce by half (~3 min).
3. Add cream, simmer 2 min. Turn heat to LOW. Add butter one at a time while stirring – sauce will thicken and turn glossy. Strain (optional), return back into pan. Add fish into sauce, leave 30 sec. Sprinkle with parsley, serve!

#recipetineats #fishrecipe #sauceforfish

Going for gold for the fastest fish dinner on record - cooked in 2 1/2 minutes flat! Seared on the outside, rare on the inside, this is the ONLY way tuna steaks should be cooked! - N x ❤️

Tuna Steak 

2 x 180 – 200g (6.5 – 7oz) tuna (skinless, boneless). 2.5-3cm / 1-1.2" thick, FRESH
1 tsp olive oil, 1/4 tsp sea salt, 1/8 tsp black pepper

COOKING: 2 tsp olive oil , or oil spray

1. Use fingers to lightly rub oil on tuna, sprinkle with salt and pepper. Heat heavy based skillet, preferably with grill lines, on high heat until smoking. If your skillet is not well seasoned with oil, brush with olive oil OR take off heat then spray with oil (never spray ON stove!).
2. Cook tuna 45 sec, then rotate 45 degrees and cook for another 45 sec (for criss cross). If you don’t have grille pan, just leave tuna for 1 ½ min.
3. Flip tuna, cook 1 min or until internal temp is 48°C / 118°F. Rest on rack set over tray for 5 min to cool to room temp - easier slicing and nicer to eat.
4. Sauce options (see website for links): Sauce Vierge (below), chimichurri, salsa, Asian sesame, salsa verde, pici de gallo.

French Sauce Vierge option (pictured) – mix, taste, add more salt if desired,
5 ½ tbsp extra virgin olive oil, 2 tbsp lemon juice, 2 tomatoes seeded diced 0.8cm / 1/3”, 12 black olives pitted and cut into thin strips, 2 anchovy fillets*, 1/2 tsp garlic*, 1 tsp parsley*, 1/2 tsp chives*, 1/2 tsp tarragon leaves*, 1/4 tsp each salt & pepper.
Use straight away or keep for a day – sprinkle on salads, omelette, like salsa on chicken, fish, prawns/shrimp. 

#recipetineats #tunasteak #tuna #healthy #quickdinner

That elusive combination of fork-tender meat and insanely crispy crackling…. Ladies and gentlemen - it’s slow roasted crispy pork belly time. 🎶JUMP ON IT! 🎶- N x ❤️

Crispy Slow Roasted Pork Belly
.
Cooked “confit-style” using a foil boat to catch the fat as it melts so the flesh cooks in its own fat! Extra flavour and juiciness.
.
1kg / 2 lb pork belly with skin on , NOT SCORED. Look for 3 - 3.5cm / 1.2 - 1.6" thick, even thickness with flat, unwrinkled skin, preferably not vac-packed*
1 1/2 tsp olive oil , divided
1/2 tsp fennel powder / ground fennel seeds , optional
1 tsp salt , cooking/kosher salt (or 7/8 tsp table salt), divided
1/4 tsp black pepper 
.
1. Pat skin dry and leave uncovered in fridge overnight, to really get the skin nice and dry (highly recommended).
2. Rub flesh with 1 tsp oil, 1/2 tsp salt, 1/2 tsp fennel and 1/4 tsp pepper. Turn over, wrap flesh like an open “box” with double layer of foil. Pat skin dry, rub with 1/2 tsp oil, sprinkle 1/2 tsp salt evenly all over skin.
3. Roast 2.5 hrs at 140°C/325°F (120°C fan), tighten foil after about 1.5 hrs. Remove from oven (skin should be rubbery still), increase heat to 240°C/465°F. Remove pork from foil, place on rack on tray. Use scrunched up balls of foil to prop belly up so skin is as level as possible – for best crackling result.
4. Roast 30 min, rotating after 15 min then as needed, until crackling is golden, puffy and crispy. Pork is so flavourful because of “confit” style cooking that you don’t even need a sauce! Pictured in video with apple sauce + jus, fine dining style. Also see recipe on website for a bunch of other serving sauce ideas.
.
* If you can only get vac packed, highly recommend doing the overnight fridge dry
